    "html": "<div style=\"position:relative;width:100%;height:100%;background:radial-gradient(at 40% 20%, #1A237E15 0px, transparent 50%), radial-gradient(at 80% 0%, #50290010 0px, transparent 50%), radial-gradient(at 0% 50%, #5F78DA12 0px, transparent 50%), var(--surface-light);background-color:var(--surface-light);overflow:hidden;\">\n            <div style=\"opacity: 0.04; position: absolute; z-index: 1; pointer-events: none; inset: 0; background: var(--texture-grain)\"></div>\n            \n            <div class=\"slide-content\" style=\"position:relative;z-index:10;padding:80px 48px var(--space-12);display:flex;flex-direction:column;justify-content:center;height:100%;width:100%;box-sizing:border-box;overflow:hidden;\">\n                <div style=\"max-width:320px;margin:0 auto;text-align:left;width:100%;box-sizing:border-box;display:flex;flex-direction:column;justify-content:center;height:100%;overflow:hidden;padding-bottom:var(--space-2);\">\n            <h2 style=\"font-family:Plus Jakarta Sans;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#090B0F;margin:0 0 16px;line-height:1.2;\">The Proof</h2>\n            <div style=\"margin-top:4px;\"><p style=\"font-family:Plus Jakarta Sans;font-size:14px;color:#3F424B;margin:0 0 12px;line-height:1.6;\">The first real benchmark: 47 slides rendered in 0.8 seconds. The Python reference implementation took 12 seconds. The skeptics weren&#x27;t wrong about difficulty \u2014 they were wrong about feasibility.</p></div>\n        </div>\n            </div>\n        </div>",
